1. **Project Title**  
    Payroll Database Management System

2. **Objective**  
   To design and implement a payroll management database that demonstrates DBA skills such as schema design, user access control, query optimization, backup & recovery, and automation using triggers & stored procedures.

3. **Tech Stack**  
   PostgreSQL  
   DBeaver / pgAdmin

4. **Features**  
   ‚úÖ Database schema for departments, employees, and leaves  
   ‚úÖ Role-based access control (admin, manager, readonly)  
   ‚úÖ Query optimization with indexing  
   ‚úÖ Backup & restore with pg\_dump and psql  
   ‚úÖ Trigger-based salary change logging  
   ‚úÖ Stored procedure for salary bonus updates

**üìä Sample Queries**

**1\. View all Employees with Department**  
     
SELECT \* FROM employee;

**2\. Average Salary by Department (Business Query)**

SELECT d.dept\_name, AVG(e.salary)  
FROM employee e  
JOIN department d ON e.dept\_id \= d.dept\_id  
GROUP BY d.dept\_name;

**3\. Salary Bonus Automation**

\-- Add 10% bonus to all employees  
SELECT update\_salary\_with\_bonus(10);

**4\. View Salary Change Logs (Audit Trail)**

SELECT \* FROM salary\_log;

**5\. Active Employees View**

SELECT \* FROM active\_employees;

**üîê Backup & Restore** 

Implemented database backup and restore using \`pg\_dump\` and \`psql\`.

‚Üí Backup Command

pg\_dump \-U postgres \-d payroll\_db \-F p \-f payroll\_backup.sql

This generates a full SQL backup of the database.

### 

**Restore Command**

psql \-U postgres \-d payroll\_db\_restored \-f payroll\_backup.sql

This restores the database into a new instance (payroll\_db\_restored).
